1
00:00:01,026 --> 00:00:28,957
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sammasambuddhasa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sammasambuddhasa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sammasambuddhasa Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-enlightened one.

2
00:00:33,713 --> 00:00:41,091
I think at the time of the Buddha in his own time there were

3
00:00:41,323 --> 00:00:46,030
various ideas around this word karma.

4
00:00:47,051 --> 00:01:09,998
We know it more commonly through the Sanskrit word karma with an R, but the way that Theravada spells it was just K-A-M-M-A, which is Pali, which is what the scriptures are actually written in, which would have been a dialect around modern Varanasi, that sort of, you know, around the Ganges.

5
00:01:11,480 --> 00:01:15,692
And it's a core sort of teaching really.

6
00:01:16,796 --> 00:01:23,498
It's one of his main insights upon liberation, upon his awakening.

7
00:01:23,865 --> 00:01:50,177
He has what we, he talks of his three, excuse me, three things that happened to him upon awakening, upon, you know, the immediacy afterwards, afterwards awakening, was that he was able to see his past lives and see how his ethical decisions had brought him to this place and how they caused him to suffer and to put him into dire straits.

8
00:01:50,662 --> 00:02:00,993
And then he was able to see beings moving from one realm to the other, according to their ethical decisions, their moral decisions.

9
00:02:01,974 --> 00:02:07,361
And what was then a personal understanding, a personal law, became a cosmic law.

10
00:02:09,242 --> 00:02:17,852
And the third thing that he recognized was that all his defilements had gone, so there was nothing negative within his character and personality anymore.

11
00:02:19,925 --> 00:02:23,187
So these are known as the three knowledges.

12
00:02:24,748 --> 00:02:48,531
And it's very difficult, I know that you may come across Buddhist speakers who sort of deny rebirth and things like that, but it's very difficult to read the scriptures without coming to the conclusion that he definitely did understand the process as being very long-term over lifetimes.

13
00:02:50,013 --> 00:02:56,225
And the reason for that was that we begin from this point of not knowing.

14
00:02:57,472 --> 00:03:02,278
This not knowing is not a culpable state.

15
00:03:02,419 --> 00:03:08,328
It's often translated as ignorance, this word, and I'm referring to avijja, for those of you who know it.

16
00:03:09,729 --> 00:03:17,681
It's referred to as ignorance, and that has a sort of pejorative meaning, as though you should have known, you know, you've not been such an idiot.

17
00:03:17,701 --> 00:03:20,746
But it's actually a very neutral state of simply not knowing.

18
00:03:22,127 --> 00:03:24,170
And this not knowing...

19
00:03:24,842 --> 00:03:35,056
then it's your basic intelligence, that which does not know, finding itself in a situation makes sense of it.

20
00:03:35,437 --> 00:03:42,686
And it's made sense of it for us by the society, culture, history that we find ourselves in.

21
00:03:42,746 --> 00:03:48,993
And it's from there that we build up our characters and personalities.

22
00:03:51,151 --> 00:03:58,408
So that we could say that any given moment there is underlying this state of just not knowing.

23
00:03:59,831 --> 00:04:09,074
And because of that we've moved into a situation which is an understanding

24
00:04:09,055 --> 00:04:38,826
and this fundamental understanding as to who we are or what we are or where we're going to is actually the fundamental attitude that causes everything else so one of the main understandings that we have is that we are human beings this is a big problem

25
00:04:40,983 --> 00:05:06,247
conventionally there's no problem everybody we know that we're human beings as opposed to primates and the cat and all that sort of stuff but when we talk when we actually say to ourselves well I'm a human being our energies go into trying to make this life the end the purpose of our living

26
00:05:06,329 --> 00:05:14,285
So, especially these days where you see people have lost, many people have lost any spiritual or religious foundation.

27
00:05:14,805 --> 00:05:16,028
There is only this life.

28
00:05:17,651 --> 00:05:20,377
And when you ask yourself, what is it that I really want?

29
00:05:20,697 --> 00:05:22,781
You know, really deep down, what is that really want?

30
00:05:23,023 --> 00:05:25,687
I think you can just come across the word, I want to be happy.

31
00:05:25,987 --> 00:05:27,249
You just want to be happy.

32
00:05:28,790 --> 00:05:32,055
And this happiness is then sought for in the world.

33
00:05:32,834 --> 00:05:35,978
And what is it that brings us happiness as we understand it?

34
00:05:36,800 --> 00:05:46,129
It's sensual pleasure, it's relationships, it's our work sometimes, our hobbies, you see.

35
00:05:46,470 --> 00:05:55,319
So there's an absolute investment in life as a place where if you can just get it right, you'll be happy.

36
00:05:55,300 --> 00:06:24,918
and what this produces is a relationship to life and a relationship to people and what we have as collections we collect things we collect money we collect our job we collect people and that collection the word that's normally come for it is attachment and the reason we're attached to it is because this makes me happy

37
00:06:24,899 --> 00:06:36,439
So I'm attached to the things I own, to my house, to my HDTV and all that sort of stuff because this is what's making me happy, that's where I actually put the investment.

38
00:06:38,242 --> 00:06:45,675
Unfortunately, having created these little islands of happiness around objects,

39
00:06:47,899 --> 00:06:54,262
Anything that begins to upset that, I form a very negative relationship towards.

40
00:06:54,762 --> 00:06:55,687
And that's your aversion.

41
00:06:56,389 --> 00:06:59,901
Anything that undermines my happiness becomes my enemy.

42
00:07:00,843 --> 00:07:04,447
And if the enemy is too big, then I become frightened, I get very anxious.

43
00:07:05,829 --> 00:07:28,824
So there you've got, from this fundamental misunderstanding, which is often termed a delusion, you have a basic relationship to life of having to collect things around you, hold on to things, keep things, which are going to make me happy, and I've got to make sure that that mustn't be upset.

44
00:07:29,581 --> 00:07:49,209
So from that sense of attachment, often referred to as greed, it's not quite that word, just attachment, we get the aversion, which splits into two relationships, one of aversion, not liking, pushing away, and one of running away, anxiety, fear.

45
00:07:50,978 --> 00:08:20,766
so from that basic relationship we produce our kamma now kamma in the buddhist teaching is a technical word which actually only refers to an action that's what it really means just an action and whatever we do whether it's an act of thought an act of speech or something that we actually do physically an action as such

46
00:08:20,745 --> 00:08:25,254
is driven from that particular delusion.

47
00:08:26,875 --> 00:08:36,371
So constantly, we're in a constant relationship of trying to jiggle the world to make sure that we're sort of happy.

48
00:08:37,072 --> 00:08:43,563
Even as you're sitting here, you might find that without you knowing it, you become slightly uncomfortable in your seat and you shift position.

49
00:08:44,505 --> 00:08:58,583
If we just watch ourselves throughout the day, we're constantly moving towards comfort, towards what makes us feel happy, always trying to escape what is uncomfortable, what is making us feel unhappy.

50
00:08:59,205 --> 00:09:03,149
And these actions, this is what the Buddha has referred to as kamma.

51
00:09:03,169 --> 00:09:04,270
These are your actions.

52
00:09:07,034 --> 00:09:08,876
And...

53
00:09:09,328 --> 00:09:19,144
In dependent origination, which is the Buddha's psychology as to how we create our misery, we'll go on to happiness towards the end of the talk, a real happiness.

54
00:09:19,163 --> 00:09:21,727
So I don't want to get you too depressed.

55
00:09:21,748 --> 00:09:29,700
And they said the way that we create this unhappiness, he points out very clearly through the teaching of dependent origination.

56
00:09:29,679 --> 00:09:43,499
This dependent origination, you might come across in later Buddhism, was expanded completely into a sort of universal concept of interrelatedness, everything being dependent on something else.

57
00:09:44,399 --> 00:09:54,253
But in the Buddha's original teaching, although you may find those sorts of ideas, he's very centered upon our inner personal psychology.

58
00:09:54,232 --> 00:10:00,265
So what happens to us on the outside is not really material to the process of liberation.

59
00:10:01,167 --> 00:10:07,179
It's always what's happening inside us which is actually causing either the misery or the escape from misery.

60
00:10:08,965 --> 00:10:27,902
So, for instance, if I'm in the quiet coach of a train, I'm sure you've all been in a quiet coach, and somebody decides to use their mobile, you see, and it's what's happening in me that's turning the quiet coach into a really small little hell realm.

61
00:10:27,881 --> 00:10:46,751
because I'm saying they shouldn't be doing that, this is a terrible thing, it's really unethical and punishable by law and they shouldn't be doing it and I'm getting all heated and hot about it and all that's being created internally, it's not being created by the phone call.

62
00:10:46,731 --> 00:11:11,101
you see and then of course suddenly my phone goes off and this phone is of course very important so I've got to make it so I presume everybody else will understand that so you can see that from this relation from if you look at if we look at ourselves throughout the day you'll see that there's always something coming at us from the outside there's always something impinging upon our consciousness

63
00:11:11,081 --> 00:11:14,788
And there's always this response, right?

64
00:11:14,807 --> 00:11:16,931
You can call it a reaction rather than a response.

65
00:11:17,993 --> 00:11:26,626
Because the reaction is already dictated to by our past actions which have produced certain habits, certain patterns of behavior within us.

66
00:11:27,687 --> 00:11:34,923
And it's really beginning to see how these are produced, which allows us to see where the escape is.

67
00:11:36,385 --> 00:11:42,759
So, so long as people say to themselves, you know, the reason I'm unhappy is because of the government.

68
00:11:42,740 --> 00:12:11,532
or because of bankers or because of my neighbour or because of my kids and also if I am constantly thinking that the other person is causing is the direct cause of my misery then I'm always going to be in some sort of some sort of relationship to the world of trying to change the world I'm always trying to do something I'm always trying to do something out there which is going to make me happy in here

69
00:12:11,511 --> 00:12:34,852
and I'm sure we've all experienced people who've tried to change us and it's the last thing we individually want another person to do so as soon as you try to change somebody else or try to change a situation then you often find yourself in this very antagonistic position where in fact you find yourself making things worse

70
00:12:35,726 --> 00:12:49,561
Now, if we go through the Buddha's teaching about how we create these mental states, you see very clearly that he puts the accent on a moment, the moment of identity.

71
00:12:50,240 --> 00:12:56,727
So, there is independent origination, this moment where something impinges upon us through the five senses.

72
00:12:56,748 --> 00:12:58,690
He calls it also the sixth sense.

73
00:12:58,710 --> 00:13:03,894
So, it's something which is coming from the outside, somebody says something, or you see something,

74
00:13:03,875 --> 00:13:08,206
And as it were, it comes into the mind, into consciousness.

75
00:13:09,107 --> 00:13:12,054
I'm using these words very loosely because they have so much meaning these days.

76
00:13:12,655 --> 00:13:19,734
It comes into the mind as a sort of primary object, which is recognized, acknowledged.

77
00:13:19,774 --> 00:13:21,477
It's recognized, acknowledged.

78
00:13:21,457 --> 00:13:28,638
So if we're sitting here now and suddenly a bell goes off, the first thing would be the actual acknowledgement that there is a bell going off.

79
00:13:28,918 --> 00:13:30,543
That's your first thing.

80
00:13:31,065 --> 00:13:36,801
Then it's taken inside, you see, and suddenly we attach a meaning to that bell.

81
00:13:36,780 --> 00:13:38,322
which is it's an alarm bell.

82
00:13:39,105 --> 00:13:44,351
So as soon as an alarm bell goes, then you get the meaning that there may be fire, etc.

83
00:13:44,413 --> 00:13:47,778
So you get higher levels of understanding of what the alarm bell might mean.

84
00:13:48,938 --> 00:13:56,390
And then the understanding comes in towards the end of that process of, I have to get out of here.

85
00:13:57,692 --> 00:14:03,902
Now, if you take, for instance, just a normal thing, like you're in a shop and you want to buy something,

86
00:14:03,881 --> 00:14:09,006
the normal sentence would be, I want that, right?

87
00:14:09,027 --> 00:14:09,787
I want that.

88
00:14:10,168 --> 00:14:14,631
But what the Buddha is actually pointing out is that psychologically it's the reverse.

89
00:14:14,652 --> 00:14:32,707
So first of all, you see Costa coffee, and you smell Costa, and you smell the coffee, and that's your first recognition, that's the point, as it were, of perception, of cognition, that this is Costa coffee.

90
00:14:32,687 --> 00:14:40,155
And then with that, you see, there arises the relationship that we might have developed with Costa Coffee, which is our want.

91
00:14:40,976 --> 00:14:43,179
So there's your wanting coming in.

92
00:14:43,460 --> 00:14:45,842
So first of all, there's just the simple contact.

93
00:14:46,423 --> 00:14:52,629
Then there's this wanting that comes, which is there because of our past experience with Costa Coffee.

94
00:14:54,091 --> 00:15:00,619
Because once you've created an act and you redo that act, you are constantly reinforcing a certain relationship.

95
00:15:02,118 --> 00:15:05,283
And once that's happened, then the I comes in.

96
00:15:05,423 --> 00:15:07,628
So it's coffee, want, I.

97
00:15:07,849 --> 00:15:09,932
That's the process in terms of psychology.

98
00:15:10,533 --> 00:15:22,375
Now, it's only at that point of I, with the identification that I want this coffee, that you get the empowerment of that desire, and in you go and buy yourself some coffee.

99
00:15:23,136 --> 00:15:24,379
And that's the becoming.

100
00:15:24,359 --> 00:15:36,777
So this word becoming in Buddhist teaching is this constant reinvention of the self, constant reinvention of me, a constant playing around with who I am and where I want to go.

101
00:15:36,836 --> 00:15:45,490
So an identity is not something static, it's always something that's moving with time and place and with what it is I'm experiencing.

102
00:15:47,022 --> 00:16:00,956
Now, the reason why this act of karma, this action, to understand this is so important because when we understand things are happening in that way, then you can see the escape.

103
00:16:02,038 --> 00:16:16,995
If it happened the other way, if the identity came in immediately, there would be, as it were, no gap, not enough a gap between the I want this and the actual action.

104
00:16:16,975 --> 00:16:45,395
because the I is that point where you've absorbed into the wanting it's like you've become the wanting but when we're actually awake and I'm not talking about sitting here in meditation I'm talking about just walking down the street when you're actually with that earlier process of wanting as a force within you of actually moving you towards the object then there's no identity

105
00:16:45,712 --> 00:16:49,085
You're still aware of the desire.

106
00:16:49,726 --> 00:16:52,456
And being aware of something means you can't be it.

107
00:16:53,681 --> 00:16:55,807
You've already created a separation.

108
00:16:56,513 --> 00:17:02,960
Now when you look into that separation, then you begin to understand what the Buddha's teaching about not-self is.

109
00:17:03,760 --> 00:17:06,763
Because if you separate from something, you can't be it.

110
00:17:08,226 --> 00:17:22,622
So as soon as I'm walking down the street and I get this wonderful whiff of Costa coffee, you see, if I'm aware of that desire arising in me, you see, then it creates a little distance, it creates a little separation.

111
00:17:22,602 --> 00:17:33,692
And that separation allows me just enough time to reflect upon whether I should go in and have this Costa coffee or not.

112
00:17:33,712 --> 00:17:40,440
So this becomes a deep and profound moral problem for anybody into trying to undo past conditioning.

113
00:17:40,941 --> 00:17:50,871
So now you might say to yourself, well, yes I will you see, it could be so overpowering that in fact you miss that moment and before you know it you're there drinking your coffee.

114
00:17:50,851 --> 00:18:05,523
I'm sure this happens to you at home, where the idea that you're doing things, or at work you're doing things, and then suddenly tea, and before you know it you drink your tea, and then you suddenly realize you've drunk your tea, and you don't remember drinking your tea, so you may as well have another cup.

115
00:18:05,544 --> 00:18:08,906
So this is called the unmindful life, you see.

116
00:18:09,248 --> 00:18:14,432
So what you're trying to do is come back on that process to regain control over your life.

117
00:18:14,732 --> 00:18:15,333
That's what it is.

118
00:18:15,393 --> 00:18:20,857
It's about actually going back to a position where you're in control and not the habits that you've created.

119
00:18:20,837 --> 00:18:47,705
remember nobody's correct now that's the other of insight nobody's created these habits within us we've done it through the mechanisms of our own psychology and it's seeing how we're entrapped in these particular habitual formations right these were for those of you know these are cut these are your sankaras that you begin to try to pull out of it now you don't pull out of it until it begins to hurt

120
00:18:48,428 --> 00:19:18,351
so long as you're getting your up comers from these habitual actions and you're getting some pleasure and the pleasure is and the happiness is outweighing the unhappiness or the effort that you have to make to get these happiness then you tend to stay on that treadmill you tend to keep moving you see but as soon as something sort of disappears from that equation and you find that actually there's more suffering involved than there was than there is happiness then

121
00:19:18,330 --> 00:19:38,819
that's when you start looking for some sort of spiritual practice to help you out of the hole so if for instance you have a habit of drinking tea or coffee a lot and it's only when the doctor says you've got a really high blood pressure here

122
00:19:38,799 --> 00:19:59,458
you better come off the coffee something comes out something destroys that easy equation that there was with coffee equals happiness now coffee equals happiness but it also equals ill health and suddenly you have to pull yourself out as you pull yourself out of any habitual action some of it may be

123
00:19:59,438 --> 00:20:08,794
deeply ingrained from early childhood, and some of it may be physical, like smoking or alcohol, then what you come across is this enormous resistance.

124
00:20:10,757 --> 00:20:16,906
The whole psychological mechanism has been set up to find happiness in this particular habitude.

125
00:20:16,886 --> 00:20:19,270
And suddenly you're saying, well, I want to stop that.

126
00:20:20,573 --> 00:20:26,801
And then there has to be this pulling back, which is the suffering of coming off a habit.

127
00:20:27,303 --> 00:20:34,473
So if you find yourself constantly grazing throughout the day, little snacks here, snacks there,

128
00:20:34,807 --> 00:20:37,471
and you suddenly bloated into this huge balloon.

129
00:20:38,053 --> 00:20:43,299
And the doctor said, well, you know, if you don't lose weight, you're going to explode or worse, you see.

130
00:20:43,579 --> 00:20:45,102
He said, oh, God, I've got to stop, you see.

131
00:20:45,122 --> 00:20:51,270
So now you have to come off all these little snacks, which were little comfort zones where you found happiness is.

132
00:20:51,932 --> 00:20:53,133
And it's painful.

133
00:20:53,314 --> 00:20:55,737
You've got to really sort of work at it.

134
00:20:55,717 --> 00:21:13,550
And in coming off that, you see, you're beginning to realize, or we are beginning to realize, that this whole process of liberation, this whole process of karma, is tied into the whole process of ethical living, tied into the whole process of ethical living.

135
00:21:13,571 --> 00:21:18,500
And that is tied into the deep insight into how we create suffering for ourselves.

136
00:21:19,290 --> 00:21:20,792
It's all one and the same thing.

137
00:21:21,193 --> 00:21:28,605
It's not as though there's all this meditation going on with great insights into not-self and conditioning.

138
00:21:28,987 --> 00:21:35,798
And you can separate that from your daily actions because the one is an expression of the other.

139
00:21:37,432 --> 00:22:02,696
So here we are on the wheel of dependent origination, dependent meaning that every step is dependent on some step before it, or dependent on some present conditioning, that's what it means, and there's no absolute origination, nothing arises of itself, everything that arises is dependent on something else.

140
00:22:02,676 --> 00:22:09,750
So here we have this internal psychology which is trying to make sense of the world and trying to create happiness for itself.

141
00:22:11,232 --> 00:22:20,151
And every time we go into that mode of seeking happiness in the sensual world, then this wheel turns.

142
00:22:20,270 --> 00:22:23,537
It's not turning all the time, it doesn't turn when you're asleep.

143
00:22:23,517 --> 00:22:32,667
But every time it turns, it, as it were, just, you know, reinforces the habit, reinforces the habit.

144
00:22:32,688 --> 00:22:37,393
And it's only when we come off the habit that we realize how strong the habit actually is.

145
00:22:38,615 --> 00:22:40,836
So here we get this teaching of renunciation.

146
00:22:41,657 --> 00:22:49,186
Now, the Buddha himself, of course, tried these very heavy self-mortification exercises

147
00:22:49,386 --> 00:22:55,401
which had as their understanding that the problem was with the body.

148
00:22:56,241 --> 00:23:00,692
So if the body didn't have an appetite, then you'd never suffer from overeating.

149
00:23:01,614 --> 00:23:07,647
If your body didn't have any sexual organs, then you wouldn't suffer from lust.

150
00:23:07,627 --> 00:23:08,650
That was the idea.

151
00:23:09,029 --> 00:23:15,460
So, by going into self-mortification exercises, you reduced the importance of the body.

152
00:23:15,539 --> 00:23:21,429
You stopped feeding the body, thinking that as soon as you waken the body up, then desire wakes.

153
00:23:21,449 --> 00:23:23,932
Desire wakes with it.

154
00:23:23,913 --> 00:23:30,284
So he found that to be pretty useless, definitely not on the path, and just more suffering.

155
00:23:30,825 --> 00:23:34,332
So he abandoned that, but he didn't abandon the idea of renunciation.

156
00:23:35,073 --> 00:23:46,713
So renunciation is the point where a person says to themselves, I have to give this up for whatever reason, might be health reasons, psychological reasons, money reasons, whatever you see.

157
00:23:46,693 --> 00:23:55,809
And you stop doing a certain action, you stop behaving in a certain way, and of course what you find is this enormous resistance.

158
00:23:56,892 --> 00:24:05,226
It can be physical, like if one of our problems has been around food, then it begins to cloy on the mind.

159
00:24:05,205 --> 00:24:20,612
So it's being able to sit with that, being able to sit with that pain where what you're actually doing is allowing the engine of that particular habit to lose power, to lose power.

160
00:24:21,314 --> 00:24:26,201
And this is where you could say the psychotherapy of Buddhism takes place.

161
00:24:27,700 --> 00:24:45,317
Once we've identified that a certain habit is unhealthy for us, then I don't know of any way in which you can undo that habit without going through the pain of allowing that desire to express itself and release its energy.

162
00:24:46,377 --> 00:24:48,640
And if you come across an easy way, please tell me.

163
00:24:49,461 --> 00:24:56,307
So you've got this habit, for instance, of taking snacks during the day, eating all the time.

164
00:24:56,557 --> 00:25:01,065
So every time you approach food, every time somebody approaches food, you see, they have to stop.

165
00:25:01,726 --> 00:25:05,834
This is a really powerful, wonderful word in English, stop, see.

166
00:25:06,615 --> 00:25:08,838
I was in Spain recently doing the Camino.

167
00:25:08,858 --> 00:25:13,126
I was greatly overjoyed to see that the road sign was stop, you see.

168
00:25:13,146 --> 00:25:15,371
Every time he came to Denver, he said, stop.

169
00:25:15,471 --> 00:25:16,894
I thought, very intelligent.

170
00:25:16,874 --> 00:25:27,732
So when you say this word stop, you see, then it's actually where it puts a break and it allows you to feel this animal, this urge for that biscuit.

171
00:25:27,752 --> 00:25:29,115
See, it comes up like that, you see.

172
00:25:29,656 --> 00:25:40,536
